      {
        depth: 6,
        title: "Black Holes, Information, and the Arrow Unresolved",
        body: `<p>Entropy refuses to stay in the kitchen of steam engines and coffee cups. In 1972, Jacob Bekenstein, then a graduate student under John Wheeler at Princeton, made a startling proposal: a black hole has entropy, and it is proportional to the area of its event horizon, not its volume. Stephen Hawking, who initially resisted the idea, soon proved that black holes radiate — emitting a faint thermal spectrum now called Hawking radiation — and pinned down the constant:</p><pre>S_BH = (k c³ A) / (4 ℏ G)</pre><p>where <code>A</code> is the horizon area, <code>c</code> the speed of light, <code>ℏ</code> the reduced Planck constant, and <code>G</code> Newton's constant. A single black hole the mass of the sun has more entropy than every star, planet, and atom in the visible universe combined. Worse, if black holes evaporate, what happens to the information about what fell in? Hawking's calculation suggested it was simply lost — a violation of unitarity, the bedrock of quantum mechanics. This is the <strong>black hole information paradox</strong>, and forty years on it is still not fully resolved, though recent work by Geoff Penington, Ahmed Almheiri, and others on "entanglement islands" suggests information may, after all, leak out in subtle correlations.</p><p>That entropy lives on a surface, not in a volume, has become the basis of the <strong>holographic principle</strong> (Gerard 't Hooft, Leonard Susskind, 1990s), the conjecture that the information content of a region of space can be encoded on its boundary. The AdS/CFT correspondence, proposed by Juan Maldacena in 1997, is the most concrete realization: a gravitational theory in a curved bulk is equivalent to a quantum field theory on its lower-dimensional boundary. Spacetime itself may be, in some sense, made of entanglement.</p><p>Closer to home, the puzzle of the <strong>arrow of time</strong> persists. Roger Penrose has argued that the entropy of the early universe — at the Big Bang — was extravagantly, almost impossibly low, perhaps one part in <code>10^(10^123)</code>. Why? No one knows. Sean Carroll and others have proposed cosmological scenarios in which our low-entropy past is a fluctuation in an eternal multiverse. Others suspect the question is malformed.</p><p>Entropy began as an accountant's trick for steam engines. It has become the thread that ties together heat, information, gravity, computation, and the deep grain of time. Whatever you study, if you study it long enough, you find Boltzmann's tombstone waiting.</p>`
      }
